Example \(\PageIndex{11}\) Find the intercepts of \(f(x)=\dfrac{(x-2)(x+3)}{(x-1)(x+2)(x-5)}\) Solution We can find the vertical intercept by evaluating the function at zero \[f(0)=\dfrac{(0-2)(0+3)}{(0-1)(0+2)(0-5)} =\dfrac{-6}{10} =-\dfrac{3}{5}
onumber \] The horizontal intercepts will occur when the function is equal to zero: \[0=\dfrac{(x-2)(x+3)}{(x-1)(x+2)(x-5)}
onumber \] This is zero when the numerator is zero \[ egin{array}{l} {0=(x-2)(x+3)} \ {x=2,\; -3} \end{array}
onumber \]
